        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "My preference would still be to use a dedicated highlight group and adjust it. This is most idiomatic way of introducing a new functionality that deals with highlighting.\r\n\r\nThe most robust choice for `DiagnosticStatuslineXxx` would be \"inverted colored\": colorful background and grey foreground. This makes diagnostics stand out quite a bit, but maybe it is a good thing. Similar to the following definitions in the 'init.lua':\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, 'DiagnosticSignError', { bg = 'NvimLightRed', fg = 'NvimDarkGrey2' })\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, 'DiagnosticSignWarn', { bg = 'NvimLightYellow', fg = 'NvimDarkGrey2' })\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, 'DiagnosticSignInfo', { bg = 'NvimLightCyan', fg = 'NvimDarkGrey2' })\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, 'DiagnosticSignHint', { bg = 'NvimLightBlue', fg = 'NvimDarkGrey2' })\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_hl(0, 'DiagnosticSignOk', { bg = 'NvimLightGreen', fg = 'NvimDarkGrey2' })\r\n```\r\n\r\nHere is how it will look with default `bg=dark`:\r\n\r\n<img width=\"2880\" height=\"1734\" alt=\"screenshot_2025-11-25_23:04:07\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d7a762e2-453f-4649-bf87-a4296d552de5\" />",
